      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The Late Bronze Age collapse was caused by a systemic failure of the palatial redistributive economy, triggered by a cascade of disruptions in the trans-Mediterranean trade network for tin and copper, which made bronze production unsustainable and unraveled the interdependent elite structures.\", \"mechanism\": \"Palatial centers depended on tightly coupled long-distance exchange of bulk metals (especially tin from Central Asia/Iberia and copper from Cyprus) to produce bronze for weapons, tools, and prestige goods. A disruption in this network—possibly due to piracy, climate shifts affecting overland routes, or political instability in intermediary zones—caused a critical shortage of tin. Without bronze, palatial elites could not reward retainers, maintain military superiority, or produce agricultural surplus, leading to rapid internal delegitimization, elite flight, and systemic collapse across interconnected states.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Archaeological evidence shows uninterrupted tin imports and stable bronze production in Mycenaean and Hittite centers through 1200 BC.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Written records from Ugarit and Hattusa document abundant tin reserves and active metal workshops immediately prior to their destruction.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Egypt survived because it controlled its own gold sources and could trade gold for tin via Red Sea routes bypassing the disrupted northern networks, and its grain-based redistributive economy was less dependent on bronze for agricultural surplus.\"}",
